### File Descriptions
```
- app.py
  The main backend Python application file implementing the web server (e.g., using Flask or similar lightweight framework).
  It handles routing for all ten pages, processes user inputs, reads/writes data from/to the local text files in the 'data' directory,
  and serves the HTML templates with dynamic content.

- requirements.txt
  Lists Python dependencies required to run the application (e.g., Flask, Jinja2, any PDF generation libraries).

- README.md
  Documentation file describing the project setup, running instructions, and overview.

- templates/
  Contains all HTML template files for the web application pages, each corresponding to one of the ten pages specified:
  - dashboard.html: Dashboard page layout and elements.
  - destinations.html: Destinations listing with search and filter.
  - destination_details.html: Detailed view of a single destination.
  - itinerary.html: Itinerary planning and management.
  - accommodations.html: Hotel search and display.
  - transportation.html: Flight booking interface.
  - packages.html: Travel packages display and booking.
  - trips.html: Trip management page.
  - booking_confirmation.html: Booking confirmation details.
  - recommendations.html: Travel recommendations and trending destinations.

- static/
  Contains static assets used by the web pages:
  - css/styles.css: Stylesheet for consistent UI styling.
  - js/scripts.js: JavaScript for client-side interactivity (e.g., filtering, navigation).
  - images/: Folder for images such as destination photos, icons, and other UI graphics.

- data/
  Stores all application data in text files as specified:
  - destinations.txt: Destination data.
  - itineraries.txt: Itinerary data.
  - hotels.txt: Hotel data.
  - flights.txt: Flight data.
  - packages.txt: Travel package data.
  - trips.txt: Trip data.
  - bookings.txt: Booking data.

This structure keeps the backend logic centralized in one Python file for simplicity, while separating frontend templates and static assets for maintainability. Data files are organized in a dedicated folder for easy access and management.
